# Build and Resolution Rules

## Build Integrity Enforcement

### 🚨 Strict No-Workaround Policy

#### PROHIBITED Practices
- Temporary fixes to resolve build errors
- Dummy data or placeholder values to bypass type checking
- Type assertions (`as any`, `as unknown`) without proper validation
- Commenting out code to make builds pass
- Disabling TypeScript strict checks or ESLint rules for convenience

### 🔧 Acceptable Type Handling

Any/unknown justification guidance lives in the project skill:
`.cursor/skills/quality-standards/SKILL.md`.

### Guidance Location
Build error resolution workflow lives in the project skill:
`.cursor/skills/root-cause-workflow/SKILL.md`.

## Problem Solving Process - Root Cause Analysis and Verification

### Required Sequence (Strict)
Follow the root-cause workflow without skipping steps.

Guidance lives in:
`.cursor/skills/root-cause-workflow/SKILL.md`.

### English Delegation Note
This content serves as the canonical source for the English variant.

### Non-Negotiables
- No skipping or compressing steps.
- If a patch fails, do not blindly retry; diagnose the mismatch first.
- Changes must remain compliant with No-Fallback, Path-Only, and event-constants rules.

## Execution Methodology (Checklist-Driven)
- For multi-step tasks, define explicit checkbox items before implementation.
- Execute in checklist order; do not start the next item until the current item is verified.
- Mark `[x]` only after runtime/build verification succeeds for that item.
- If verification fails, revert the checkbox to `[ ]`, document the exact cause, and continue with root-cause correction.
